
[1]interdict

   INTERDICT', v.t. [L. interdico, interdictum; inter and dico, to speak.]

   1. To forbid; to prohibit. An act of congress interdicted the sailing
   of vessels from our ports. Our intercourse with foreign nations was
   interdicted.

   2. To forbid communion; to cut off from the enjoyment of communion with
   a church.

   An archbishop may not only excommunicate and interdict his suffragans,
   but his vicar-general may do the same.
